<exprlist>
  <COMMENT line1="1" col1="1" line2="1" col2="40" start="201" end="240">#' Extract results from a DESeq analysis</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2" col1="1" line2="2" col2="2" start="401" end="402">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="3" col1="1" line2="3" col2="97" start="601" end="697">#' \code{results} extracts a result table from a DESeq analysis giving base means across samples,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="4" col1="1" line2="4" col2="87" start="801" end="887">#' log2 fold changes, standard errors, test statistics, p-values and adjusted p-values;</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="5" col1="1" line2="5" col2="93" start="1001" end="1093">#' \code{resultsNames} returns the names of the estimated effects (coefficents) of the model;</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="6" col1="1" line2="6" col2="90" start="1201" end="1290">#' \code{removeResults} returns a \code{DESeqDataSet} object with results columns removed.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="7" col1="1" line2="7" col2="2" start="1401" end="1402">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="8" col1="1" line2="8" col2="68" start="1601" end="1668">#' The results table when printed will provide the information about</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="9" col1="1" line2="9" col2="89" start="1801" end="1889">#' the comparison, e.g. "log2 fold change (MAP): condition treated vs untreated", meaning</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="10" col1="1" line2="10" col2="79" start="2001" end="2079">#' that the estimates are of log2(treated / untreated), as would be returned by</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="11" col1="1" line2="11" col2="56" start="2201" end="2256">#' \code{contrast=c("condition","treated","untreated")}.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="12" col1="1" line2="12" col2="86" start="2401" end="2486">#' Multiple results can be returned for analyses beyond a simple two group comparison,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="13" col1="1" line2="13" col2="76" start="2601" end="2676">#' so \code{results} takes arguments \code{contrast} and \code{name} to help</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="14" col1="1" line2="14" col2="78" start="2801" end="2878">#' the user pick out the comparisons of interest for printing a results table.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="15" col1="1" line2="15" col2="81" start="3001" end="3081">#' The use of the \code{contrast} argument is recommended for exact specification</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="16" col1="1" line2="16" col2="58" start="3201" end="3258">#' of the levels which should be compared and their order.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="17" col1="1" line2="17" col2="3" start="3401" end="3403">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="18" col1="1" line2="18" col2="78" start="3601" end="3678">#' If \code{results} is run without specifying \code{contrast} or \code{name},</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="19" col1="1" line2="19" col2="78" start="3801" end="3878">#' it will return the comparison of the last level of the last variable in the</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="20" col1="1" line2="20" col2="92" start="4001" end="4092">#' design formula over the first level of this variable. For example, for a simple two-group</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="21" col1="1" line2="21" col2="83" start="4201" end="4283">#' comparison, this would return the log2 fold changes of the second group over the</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="22" col1="1" line2="22" col2="85" start="4401" end="4485">#' first group (the reference level). Please see examples below and in the vignette. </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="23" col1="1" line2="23" col2="2" start="4601" end="4602">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="24" col1="1" line2="24" col2="74" start="4801" end="4874">#' The argument \code{contrast} can be used to generate results tables for</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="25" col1="1" line2="25" col2="72" start="5001" end="5072">#' any comparison of interest, for example, the log2 fold change between</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="26" col1="1" line2="26" col2="72" start="5201" end="5272">#' two levels of a factor, and its usage is described below. It can also</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="27" col1="1" line2="27" col2="51" start="5401" end="5451">#' accomodate more complicated numeric comparisons.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="28" col1="1" line2="28" col2="65" start="5601" end="5665">#' Note that \code{contrast} will set to 0 the estimated LFC in a</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="29" col1="1" line2="29" col2="70" start="5801" end="5870">#' comparison of two groups, where all of the counts in the two groups</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="30" col1="1" line2="30" col2="66" start="6001" end="6066">#' are equal to 0 (while other groups have positive counts), while</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="31" col1="1" line2="31" col2="57" start="6201" end="6257">#' \code{name} will not automatically set these LFC to 0.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="32" col1="1" line2="32" col2="45" start="6401" end="6445">#' The test statistic used for a contrast is:</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="33" col1="1" line2="33" col2="2" start="6601" end="6602">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="34" col1="1" line2="34" col2="76" start="6801" end="6876">#' \deqn{ c^t \beta / \sqrt{c^t \Sigma c } }{ c' beta / sqrt( c' Sigma c ) }</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="35" col1="1" line2="35" col2="2" start="7001" end="7002">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="36" col1="1" line2="36" col2="70" start="7201" end="7270">#' The argument \code{name} can be used to generate results tables for</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="37" col1="1" line2="37" col2="88" start="7401" end="7488">#' individual effects, which must be individual elements of \code{resultsNames(object)}.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="38" col1="1" line2="38" col2="74" start="7601" end="7674">#' These individual effects could represent continuous covariates, effects</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="39" col1="1" line2="39" col2="60" start="7801" end="7860">#' for individual levels, or individual interaction effects.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="40" col1="1" line2="40" col2="3" start="8001" end="8003">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="41" col1="1" line2="41" col2="75" start="8201" end="8275">#' Information on the comparison which was used to build the results table,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="42" col1="1" line2="42" col2="92" start="8401" end="8492">#' and the statistical test which was used for p-values (Wald test or likelihood ratio test)</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="43" col1="1" line2="43" col2="81" start="8601" end="8681">#' is stored within the object returned by \code{results}. This information is in</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="44" col1="1" line2="44" col2="89" start="8801" end="8889">#' the metadata columns of the results table, which is accessible by calling \code{mcols}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="45" col1="1" line2="45" col2="71" start="9001" end="9071">#' on the \code{\link{DESeqResults}} object returned by \code{results}.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="46" col1="1" line2="46" col2="2" start="9201" end="9202">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="47" col1="1" line2="47" col2="15" start="9401" end="9415">#' On p-values:</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="48" col1="1" line2="48" col2="3" start="9601" end="9603">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="49" col1="1" line2="49" col2="74" start="9801" end="9874">#' By default, independent filtering is performed to select a set of genes</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="50" col1="1" line2="50" col2="70" start="10001" end="10070">#' for multiple test correction which maximizes the number of adjusted</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="51" col1="1" line2="51" col2="75" start="10201" end="10275">#' p-values less than a given critical value \code{alpha} (by default 0.1).</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="52" col1="1" line2="52" col2="75" start="10401" end="10475">#' See the reference in this man page for details on independent filtering.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="53" col1="1" line2="53" col2="70" start="10601" end="10670">#' The filter used for maximizing the number of rejections is the mean</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="54" col1="1" line2="54" col2="55" start="10801" end="10855">#' of normalized counts for all samples in the dataset.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="55" col1="1" line2="55" col2="59" start="11001" end="11059">#' Several arguments from the \code{filtered_p} function of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="56" col1="1" line2="56" col2="67" start="11201" end="11267">#' the genefilter package (used within the \code{results} function)</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="57" col1="1" line2="57" col2="67" start="11401" end="11467">#' are provided here to control the independent filtering behavior.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="58" col1="1" line2="58" col2="61" start="11601" end="11661">#' In DESeq2 version &gt;= 1.10, the threshold that is chosen is</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="59" col1="1" line2="59" col2="50" start="11801" end="11850">#' the lowest quantile of the filter for which the</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="60" col1="1" line2="60" col2="59" start="12001" end="12059">#' number of rejections is close to the peak of a curve fit</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="61" col1="1" line2="61" col2="57" start="12201" end="12257">#' to the number of rejections over the filter quantiles.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="62" col1="1" line2="62" col2="65" start="12401" end="12465">#' 'Close to' is defined as within 1 residual standard deviation.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="63" col1="1" line2="63" col2="77" start="12601" end="12677">#' The adjusted p-values for the genes which do not pass the filter threshold</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="64" col1="1" line2="64" col2="25" start="12801" end="12825">#' are set to \code{NA}. </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="65" col1="1" line2="65" col2="3" start="13001" end="13003">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="66" col1="1" line2="66" col2="60" start="13201" end="13260">#' By default, \code{results} assigns a p-value of \code{NA}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="67" col1="1" line2="67" col2="75" start="13401" end="13475">#' to genes containing count outliers, as identified using Cook's distance.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="68" col1="1" line2="68" col2="68" start="13601" end="13668">#' See the \code{cooksCutoff} argument for control of this behavior.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="69" col1="1" line2="69" col2="70" start="13801" end="13870">#' Cook's distances for each sample are accessible as a matrix "cooks"</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="70" col1="1" line2="70" col2="92" start="14001" end="14092">#' stored in the \code{assays()} list. This measure is useful for identifying rows where the</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="71" col1="1" line2="71" col2="69" start="14201" end="14269">#' observed counts might not fit to a Negative Binomial distribution.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="72" col1="1" line2="72" col2="2" start="14401" end="14402">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="73" col1="1" line2="73" col2="80" start="14601" end="14680">#' For analyses using the likelihood ratio test (using \code{\link{nbinomLRT}}),</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="74" col1="1" line2="74" col2="75" start="14801" end="14875">#' the p-values are determined solely by the difference in deviance between</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="75" col1="1" line2="75" col2="75" start="15001" end="15075">#' the full and reduced model formula. A single log2 fold change is printed</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="76" col1="1" line2="76" col2="73" start="15201" end="15273">#' in the results table for consistency with other results table outputs,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="77" col1="1" line2="77" col2="67" start="15401" end="15467">#' however the test statistic and p-values may nevertheless involve</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="78" col1="1" line2="78" col2="48" start="15601" end="15648">#' the testing of one or more log2 fold changes.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="79" col1="1" line2="79" col2="75" start="15801" end="15875">#' Which log2 fold change is printed in the results table can be controlled</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="80" col1="1" line2="80" col2="75" start="16001" end="16075">#' using the \code{name} argument, or by default this will be the estimated</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="81" col1="1" line2="81" col2="67" start="16201" end="16267">#' coefficient for the last element of \code{resultsNames(object)}.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="82" col1="1" line2="82" col2="2" start="16401" end="16402">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="83" col1="1" line2="83" col2="88" start="16601" end="16688">#' If \code{useT=TRUE} was specified when running \code{DESeq} or \code{nbinomWaldTest},</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="84" col1="1" line2="84" col2="73" start="16801" end="16873">#' then the p-value generated by \code{results} will also make use of the</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="85" col1="1" line2="85" col2="70" start="17001" end="17070">#' t distribution for the Wald statistic, using the degrees of freedom</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="86" col1="1" line2="86" col2="43" start="17201" end="17243">#' in \code{mcols(object)$tDegreesFreedom}.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="87" col1="1" line2="87" col2="3" start="17401" end="17403">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="88" col1="1" line2="88" col2="77" start="17601" end="17677">#' @references Richard Bourgon, Robert Gentleman, Wolfgang Huber: Independent</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="89" col1="1" line2="89" col2="71" start="17801" end="17871">#' filtering increases detection power for high-throughput experiments.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="90" col1="1" line2="90" col2="63" start="18001" end="18063">#' PNAS (2010), \url{http://dx.doi.org/10.1073/pnas.0914005107}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="91" col1="1" line2="91" col2="3" start="18201" end="18203">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="92" col1="1" line2="92" col2="45" start="18401" end="18445">#' @param object a DESeqDataSet, on which one</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="93" col1="1" line2="93" col2="54" start="18601" end="18654">#' of the following functions has already been called:</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="94" col1="1" line2="94" col2="80" start="18801" end="18880">#' \code{\link{DESeq}}, \code{\link{nbinomWaldTest}}, or \code{\link{nbinomLRT}}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="95" col1="1" line2="95" col2="74" start="19001" end="19074">#' @param contrast this argument specifies what comparison to extract from</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="96" col1="1" line2="96" col2="61" start="19201" end="19261">#' the \code{object} to build a results table. one of either:</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="97" col1="1" line2="97" col2="12" start="19401" end="19412">#' \itemize{</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="98" col1="1" line2="98" col2="57" start="19601" end="19657">#'  \item a character vector with exactly three elements:</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="99" col1="1" line2="99" col2="46" start="19801" end="19846">#' the name of a factor in the design formula,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="100" col1="1" line2="100" col2="55" start="20001" end="20055">#' the name of the numerator level for the fold change,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="101" col1="1" line2="101" col2="60" start="20201" end="20260">#' and the name of the denominator level for the fold change</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="102" col1="1" line2="102" col2="18" start="20401" end="20418">#' (simplest case)</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="103" col1="1" line2="103" col2="70" start="20601" end="20670">#'  \item a list of 2 character vectors: the names of the fold changes</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="104" col1="1" line2="104" col2="55" start="20801" end="20855">#' for the numerator, and the names of the fold changes</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="105" col1="1" line2="105" col2="23" start="21001" end="21023">#' for the denominator.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="106" col1="1" line2="106" col2="65" start="21201" end="21265">#' these names should be elements of \code{resultsNames(object)}.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="107" col1="1" line2="107" col2="66" start="21401" end="21466">#' if the list is length 1, a second element is added which is the</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="108" col1="1" line2="108" col2="46" start="21601" end="21646">#' empty character vector, \code{character()}.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="109" col1="1" line2="109" col2="76" start="21801" end="21876">#' (more general case, can be to combine interaction terms and main effects)</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="110" col1="1" line2="110" col2="52" start="22001" end="22052">#'  \item a numeric contrast vector with one element</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="111" col1="1" line2="111" col2="70" start="22201" end="22270">#' for each element in \code{resultsNames(object)} (most general case)</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="112" col1="1" line2="112" col2="4" start="22401" end="22404">#' }</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="113" col1="1" line2="113" col2="53" start="22601" end="22653">#' If specified, the \code{name} argument is ignored.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="114" col1="1" line2="114" col2="66" start="22801" end="22866">#' @param name the name of the individual effect (coefficient) for</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="115" col1="1" line2="115" col2="74" start="23001" end="23074">#' building a results table. Use this argument rather than \code{contrast}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="116" col1="1" line2="116" col2="84" start="23201" end="23284">#' for continuous variables, individual effects or for individual interaction terms.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="117" col1="1" line2="117" col2="87" start="23401" end="23487">#' The value provided to \code{name} must be an element of \code{resultsNames(object)}.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="118" col1="1" line2="118" col2="78" start="23601" end="23678">#' @param lfcThreshold a non-negative value which specifies a log2 fold change</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="119" col1="1" line2="119" col2="66" start="23801" end="23866">#' threshold. The default value is 0, corresponding to a test that</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="120" col1="1" line2="120" col2="56" start="24001" end="24056">#' the log2 fold changes are equal to zero. The user can</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="121" col1="1" line2="121" col2="78" start="24201" end="24278">#' specify the alternative hypothesis using the \code{altHypothesis} argument,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="122" col1="1" line2="122" col2="28" start="24401" end="24428">#' which defaults to testing</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="123" col1="1" line2="123" col2="74" start="24601" end="24674">#' for log2 fold changes greater in absolute value than a given threshold.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="124" col1="1" line2="124" col2="39" start="24801" end="24839">#' If \code{lfcThreshold} is specified,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="125" col1="1" line2="125" col2="72" start="25001" end="25072">#' the results are for Wald tests, and LRT p-values will be overwritten.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="126" col1="1" line2="126" col2="77" start="25201" end="25277">#' @param altHypothesis character which specifies the alternative hypothesis,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="127" col1="1" line2="127" col2="72" start="25401" end="25472">#' i.e. those values of log2 fold change which the user is interested in</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="128" col1="1" line2="128" col2="77" start="25601" end="25677">#' finding. The complement of this set of values is the null hypothesis which</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="129" col1="1" line2="129" col2="67" start="25801" end="25867">#' will be tested. If the log2 fold change specified by \code{name}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="130" col1="1" line2="130" col2="90" start="26001" end="26090">#' or by \code{contrast} is written as \eqn{ \beta }{ beta }, then the possible values for</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="131" col1="1" line2="131" col2="69" start="26201" end="26269">#' \code{altHypothesis} represent the following alternate hypotheses:</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="132" col1="1" line2="132" col2="12" start="26401" end="26412">#' \itemize{</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="133" col1="1" line2="133" col2="85" start="26601" end="26685">#' \item greaterAbs: \eqn{|\beta| &gt; \textrm{lfcThreshold} }{ |beta| &gt; lfcThreshold },</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="134" col1="1" line2="134" col2="30" start="26801" end="26830">#' and p-values are two-tailed</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="135" col1="1" line2="135" col2="83" start="27001" end="27083">#' \item lessAbs: \eqn{ |\beta| &lt; \textrm{lfcThreshold} }{ |beta| &lt; lfcThreshold },</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="136" col1="1" line2="136" col2="57" start="27201" end="27257">#' p-values are the maximum of the upper and lower tests.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="137" col1="1" line2="137" col2="88" start="27401" end="27488">#' The Wald statistic given is positive, an SE-scaled distance from the closest boundary</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="138" col1="1" line2="138" col2="78" start="27601" end="27678">#' \item greater: \eqn{ \beta &gt; \textrm{lfcThreshold} }{ beta &gt; lfcThreshold }</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="139" col1="1" line2="139" col2="77" start="27801" end="27877">#' \item less: \eqn{ \beta &lt; -\textrm{lfcThreshold} }{ beta &lt; -lfcThreshold }</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="140" col1="1" line2="140" col2="4" start="28001" end="28004">#' }</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="141" col1="1" line2="141" col2="72" start="28201" end="28272">#' @param listValues only used if a list is provided to \code{contrast}:</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="142" col1="1" line2="142" col2="93" start="28401" end="28493">#' a numeric of length two: the log2 fold changes in the list are multiplied by these values.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="143" col1="1" line2="143" col2="64" start="28601" end="28664">#' the first number should be positive and the second negative. </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="144" col1="1" line2="144" col2="36" start="28801" end="28836">#' by default this is \code{c(1,-1)}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="145" col1="1" line2="145" col2="75" start="29001" end="29075">#' @param cooksCutoff theshold on Cook's distance, such that if one or more</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="146" col1="1" line2="146" col2="71" start="29201" end="29271">#' samples for a row have a distance higher, the p-value for the row is</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="147" col1="1" line2="147" col2="83" start="29401" end="29483">#' set to NA. The default cutoff is the .99 quantile of the F(p, m-p) distribution,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="148" col1="1" line2="148" col2="85" start="29601" end="29685">#' where p is the number of coefficients being fitted and m is the number of samples.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="149" col1="1" line2="149" col2="80" start="29801" end="29880">#' Set to \code{Inf} or \code{FALSE} to disable the resetting of p-values to NA.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="150" col1="1" line2="150" col2="84" start="30001" end="30084">#' Note: this test excludes the Cook's distance of samples belonging to experimental</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="151" col1="1" line2="151" col2="30" start="30201" end="30230">#' groups with only 2 samples.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="152" col1="1" line2="152" col2="79" start="30401" end="30479">#' @param independentFiltering logical, whether independent filtering should be</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="153" col1="1" line2="153" col2="24" start="30601" end="30624">#' applied automatically</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="154" col1="1" line2="154" col2="75" start="30801" end="30875">#' @param alpha the significance cutoff used for optimizing the independent</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="155" col1="1" line2="155" col2="77" start="31001" end="31077">#' filtering (by default 0.1). If the adjusted p-value cutoff (FDR) will be a</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="156" col1="1" line2="156" col2="66" start="31201" end="31266">#' value other than 0.1, \code{alpha} should be set to that value.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="157" col1="1" line2="157" col2="75" start="31401" end="31475">#' @param filter the vector of filter statistics over which the independent</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="158" col1="1" line2="158" col2="81" start="31601" end="31681">#' filtering will be optimized. By default the mean of normalized counts is used.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="159" col1="1" line2="159" col2="73" start="31801" end="31873">#' @param theta the quantiles at which to assess the number of rejections</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="160" col1="1" line2="160" col2="29" start="32001" end="32029">#' from independent filtering</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="161" col1="1" line2="161" col2="86" start="32201" end="32286">#' @param pAdjustMethod the method to use for adjusting p-values, see \code{?p.adjust}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="162" col1="1" line2="162" col2="84" start="32401" end="32484">#' @param filterFun an optional custom function for performing independent filtering</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="164" col1="1" line2="164" col2="54" start="32801" end="32854">#' \code{filter} (the quantitity for filtering tests),</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="165" col1="1" line2="165" col2="33" start="33001" end="33033">#' \code{alpha} (the target FDR),</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="166" col1="1" line2="166" col2="74" start="33201" end="33274">#' \code{pAdjustMethod}. This function should return a DESeqResults object</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="168" col1="1" line2="168" col2="54" start="33601" end="33654">#' @param format character, either \code{"DataFrame"},</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="169" col1="1" line2="169" col2="45" start="33801" end="33845">#' \code{"GRanges"}, or \code{"GRangesList"},</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="170" col1="1" line2="170" col2="83" start="34001" end="34083">#' whether the results should be printed as a \code{\link{DESeqResults}} DataFrame,</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="173" col1="1" line2="173" col2="85" start="34601" end="34685">#' If the \code{rowRanges} is a \code{GRangesList}, and \code{GRanges} is requested, </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="174" col1="1" line2="174" col2="42" start="34801" end="34842">#' the range of each gene will be returned</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="185" col1="1" line2="185" col2="68" start="37001" end="37068">#' to generate shrunken MAP estimates using \code{\link{lfcShrink}}.</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="198" col1="1" line2="198" col2="76" start="39601" end="39676">#' @return For \code{results}: a \code{\link{DESeqResults}} object, which is</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="199" col1="1" line2="199" col2="76" start="39801" end="39876">#' a simple subclass of DataFrame. This object contains the results columns:</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="200" col1="1" line2="200" col2="69" start="40001" end="40069">#' \code{baseMean}, \code{log2FoldChange}, \code{lfcSE}, \code{stat},</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="201" col1="1" line2="201" col2="33" start="40201" end="40233">#' \code{pvalue} and \code{padj},</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="203" col1="1" line2="203" col2="74" start="40601" end="40674">#' The \code{lfcSE} gives the standard error of the \code{log2FoldChange}.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="204" col1="1" line2="204" col2="82" start="40801" end="40882">#' For the Wald test, \code{stat} is the Wald statistic: the \code{log2FoldChange}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="205" col1="1" line2="205" col2="79" start="41001" end="41079">#' divided by \code{lfcSE}, which is compared to a standard Normal distribution</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="207" col1="1" line2="207" col2="90" start="41401" end="41490">#' \code{stat} is the difference in deviance between the reduced model and the full model,</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="210" col1="1" line2="210" col2="74" start="42001" end="42074">#' For \code{resultsNames}: the names of the columns available as results,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="211" col1="1" line2="211" col2="57" start="42201" end="42257">#' usually a combination of the variable name and a level</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="212" col1="1" line2="212" col2="2" start="42401" end="42402">#'</COMMENT>

  <COMMENT line1="688" col1="1" line2="688" col2="64" start="137601" end="137664"># two low-level functions used by results() to perform contrasts</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="689" col1="1" line2="689" col2="1" start="137801" end="137801">#</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="690" col1="1" line2="690" col2="41" start="138001" end="138041"># getContrast takes a DESeqDataSet object</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="691" col1="1" line2="691" col2="44" start="138201" end="138244"># and a numeric vector specifying a contrast</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="692" col1="1" line2="692" col2="41" start="138401" end="138441"># and returns a vector of Wald statistics</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="693" col1="1" line2="693" col2="32" start="138601" end="138632"># corresponding to the contrast.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="694" col1="1" line2="694" col2="1" start="138801" end="138801">#</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="695" col1="1" line2="695" col2="42" start="139001" end="139042"># cleanContrast checks for the validity of</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="696" col1="1" line2="696" col2="54" start="139201" end="139254"># the specified contrast (numeric or character vector)</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="697" col1="1" line2="697" col2="58" start="139401" end="139458"># and turns character vector contrast into the appropriate</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="698" col1="1" line2="698" col2="25" start="139601" end="139625"># numeric vector contrast</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="699" col1="1" line2="699" col2="1" start="139801" end="139801">#</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="700" col1="1" line2="700" col2="59" start="140001" end="140059"># results() calls cleanContrast() which calls getContrast()</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="701" col1="1" line2="701" col2="1" start="140201" end="140201">#</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="702" col1="1" line2="702" col2="22" start="140401" end="140422"># the formula used is:</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="703" col1="1" line2="703" col2="29" start="140601" end="140629"># c' beta / sqrt( c' sigma c)</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="704" col1="1" line2="704" col2="38" start="140801" end="140838"># where beta is the coefficient vector</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="705" col1="1" line2="705" col2="45" start="141001" end="141045"># and sigma is the covariance matrix for beta</COMMENT>
  <expr line1="706" col1="1" line2="773" col2="1" start="141201" end="154601">
    <expr line1="706" col1="1" line2="706" col2="11" start="141201" end="141211">
      <SYMBOL line1="706" col1="1" line2="706" col2="11" start="141201" end="141211">getContrast</SYMBOL>
    </expr>
    <LEFT_ASSIGN line1="706" col1="13" line2="706" col2="14" start="141213" end="141214">&lt;-</LEFT_ASSIGN>
    <expr line1="706" col1="16" line2="773" col2="1" start="141216" end="154601">
      <FUNCTION line1="706" col1="16" line2="706" col2="23" start="141216" end="141223">function</FUNCTION>

        <expr line1="707" col1="3" line2="709" col2="3" start="141403" end="141803">
